response:
To create an Elastic Beanstalk application with an application version lifecycle, we need to perform the following steps in Terraform:

1. **Define the AWS provider:** Configure the AWS provider to manage resources in the desired region.

2. **Set up an IAM role for Elastic Beanstalk:** Elastic Beanstalk requires an EC2 instance profile to manage EC2 instances as part of its environment. We will create an IAM role and attach the necessary policies.

3. **Create an Elastic Beanstalk application:** Define the Elastic Beanstalk application resource.

4. **Set up an application version lifecycle configuration:** Create a lifecycle configuration to manage application versions. This will include rules like the number of applications to keep.

5. **Define the Elastic Beanstalk environment (optional):** Though not specifically mentioned in the request, it's common to use an environment along with the application, so we will include a basic environment setup.

Here is the complete Terraform configuration:

```hcl
provider "aws" {
  region = "us-west-2" # Choose your desired AWS region
}

resource "aws_iam_role" "eb_instance_profile" {
  name = "elasticbeanstalk-ec2-role"

  assume_role_policy = jsonencode({
    Version = "2012-10-17",
    Statement = [
      {
        Effect = "Allow",
        Principal = {
          Service = "ec2.amazonaws.com"
        },
        Action = "sts:AssumeRole"
      },
    ]
  })
}

resource "aws_iam_role_policy_attachment" "eb_instance_policy" {
  role       = aws_iam_role.eb_instance_profile.name
  policy_arn = "arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/service-role/AWSElasticBeanstalkWebTier"
}

resource "aws_iam_role_policy_attachment" "eb_ec2_ssm_policy" {
  role       = aws_iam_role.eb_instance_profile.name
  policy_arn = "arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/service-role/AmazonEC2RoleforSSM"
}

resource "aws_iam_instance_profile" "eb_instance_profile" {
  name = "elasticbeanstalk-ec2-profile"
  role = aws_iam_role.eb_instance_profile.name
}

resource "aws_elastic_beanstalk_application" "my_app" {
  name        = "my-elastic-beanstalk-app"
  description = "Sample Elastic Beanstalk Application"
}

resource "aws_elastic_beanstalk_application_version" "app_version" {
  name        = "v1"
  application = aws_elastic_beanstalk_application.my_app.name
  bucket      = "my-app-bucket" # Replace with your S3 bucket name where the application version is stored
  key         = "my-app-version.zip" # Replace with the S3 key for your application version
}

resource "aws_elastic_beanstalk_application_version_lifecycle" "version_lifecycle" {
  application = aws_elastic_beanstalk_application.my_app.name

  max_count         = 2 # Example rule to keep the last two application versions
  delete_source_from_s3 = true # Deletes the application version from S3 when it is no longer needed
}

resource "aws_elastic_beanstalk_environment" "my_environment" {
  name                = "my-environment"
  application         = aws_elastic_beanstalk_application.my_app.name
  solution_stack_name = "64bit Amazon Linux 2 v3.3.5 running PHP 8.1" # Choose the appropriate solution stack

  setting {
    namespace = "aws:autoscaling:launchconfiguration"
    name      = "IamInstanceProfile"
    value     = aws_iam_instance_profile.eb_instance_profile.name
  }
}
```

**Notes:**

- Make sure to replace `"my-app-bucket"` and `"my-app-version.zip"` with your actual S3 bucket name and key for the application version.
- Choose a suitable `solution_stack_name` that matches your application's requirements.
- Update the `region` in the AWS provider configuration to the appropriate AWS region where you intend to deploy this setup.
- To keep your application versions, adjust the `max_count` value to your needs.

